The diagnosis of KD was based on the 5th revised edition of the guidelines established by the Kawasaki Disease Research Committee in Japan in 2002 (http://kawasaki-disease.org/diagnostic/).

The included articles had to meet the following criteria: (1) either case-control study or TDT design; (2) availability of allelic frequency necessary for calculating ORs and their 95% CIs; (3) clear definition of KD, either based on the diagnostic criteria from the Committee on Rheumatic Fever, Endocarditis, andKawasaki Disease, Council on Cardiovascular Disease in the Young, American Heart Association 5, or the diagnostic guidelines for Kawasaki disease (the 5threvised edition, http://kawasaki-disease.org/diagnostic/), published by the Kawasaki DiseaseResearch Committee of Japan; (4) studies on humans.

The aim of this work was to develop and evaluate a practical approach for the 3D visualization of nano- and microscopic objects and theirinteractions with surfaces using the 3D animation software package Autodesk Maya (http://usa.autodesk.com/ maya/).
For example, the AvizoStandard software (http://www.vsg3d.com/avizo/standard) has been used to display the topographical surface features obtained from AFM analysis data 21.

Methods Software .Autodesk Maya is one of the most commonly-used software packages [along with, for example, 3Ds Max ( e.g., http://usa.autodesk.com/3ds-max/), Blender(http://www.blender.org/), Houdini (http://www.sidefx.com/), Lightwave (https:// www.lightwave3d.com/), CINEMA4D (http://www.maxon.net/products/cinema- 4d-prime/), etc.]
Maya also provides application programming interfaces (APIs) for C 11 and the Python programming language (http://www.python.org).

AFM data import .The raw data obtained using AFM were converted to a text file format using the free, open-source application Gwyddion (http://gwyddion.net/).The text files were then re-formatted as comma-separated value (CSV) files.
Rendering and post-production .The final animations were rendered using the mental ray plug-in (http://www.mentalimages.com/products/mental-ray) as a sequence of images in the TARGA format.

Parenteral Nutrition Standard 2-in-1 parenteral solutions were delivered by Fresenius Kabi (Halden, Norway) (supplementary Table 1C, http://links.lww.com/MPG/A282 ).

The protein supply was then gradually increased in both groups, mostly by enhancing the enteral supply of unfortified and later fortified human milk (10–20 mL /C1 kg/C01/C1day/C01) (supplementary Table 1A and B, http://links.lww.com/ MPG/A280 andhttp://links.lww.com/MPG/A281 ).
Enteral Nutrition All of the infants were fed human milk (supplementary Table 1D, http://links.lww.com/MPG/A283 ) (24,25).

The supply of human milk was increased equally in both groups, starting with 5 to 10 mL/kg on day 1, with a gradual increase of 10 to 20 mL /C1kg/C01/C1 day/C01(supplementary Tables 1A and B, http://links.lww.com/MPG/ A280 andhttp://links.lww.com/MPG/A281 ) (27,28).

This resulted in a significantly higher supply of energy, protein, fat, vitamin A, AA, and DHA during the first 4 weeks of hospitalization in the intervention group compared with the control group, without a significant difference in total fluid volume or amount of human milk provided (Table 3 and supple- mentary Table 2 [ http://links.lww.com/MPG/A284 ]).
